TY  - JOUR
AU  - Rotemberg, Julio J.
AU  - Scharfstein, David S.
T1  - Shareholder-Value Maximization and Product-Market Competition
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/3.3.367
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 3
IS  - 3
SP  - 367
EP  - 391
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We investigate product-market competition when managers maximize shareholder value rather than their expected discounted value of profits. If shareholders are imperfectly informed about future profitability, shareholder-value maximization can lead to either more or less aggressive product-market strategies. Lower rivals’ profits lead investors to believe that the firm’s costs are low relative to those of its rivals and that the industry’s prospects are poor. If the former (latter) inference dominates, each firm tries to lower (raise) its rivals’ profits to increase its own stock price. We also consider implications for corporate financial structure.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/3.3.367
ER  - 



