AU  - Nelson, Daniel B.
AU  - Ramaswamy, Krishna
T1  - Simple Binomial Processes as Diffusion Approximations in Financial Models
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/3.3.393
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 3
IS  - 3
SP  - 393
EP  - 430
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - A binomial approximation to a diffusion is defined as “computationally simple” if the number of nodes grows at most linearly in the number of time intervals. It is shown how to construct computationally simple binomial processes that converge weakly to commonly employed diffusions in financial models. The convergence of the sequence of bond and European option prices from these processes to the corresponding values in the diffusion limit is also demonstrated. Numerical examples from the constant elasticity of variance stock price and the Cox, Ingersoll, and Ross (1985) discount bond price are provided.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/3.3.393
ER  - 



